		<!-- Marginalia -->
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Optimi cuiusq[ue] Classis auctores, plus habent et in
						ediscendo vtilitatis;
						et in allegando dignitatis.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The best authors of this class have more, both in the study of usefullness and in the commission of dignity.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Optimum
						Exemplar, seu vivum, seu mortuum; instar omnium
						exemplorum, et pra[e]ceptorum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The best exemplar, either alive or dead: a resemblance of all examples and precepts.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Seria voluntatis contentio magnam habet
						efficiendi facultatem.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>A serious contention of will has a great faculty of accomplishment.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Viuida semper affectatio proficit plurimu[m]:
						sed e&ograve; gratiosior, qu&ograve; latentior.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>A living affectation always accomplished many things: but the more agreeable, the more hidden.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Quorsum tot dicendi, agendiq[ue] exquisita[e] formula[e], nisi vt dicatur, agaturq[ue]
						excellenti&ugrave;s, qu&agrave;m alij? Pudeat se sui, qui non omnes superat
						pra[e]sentes, sua quemq[ue] laude. Eamq[ue] intim&egrave; affectare.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Victoriam virile est. <!--JG: Why victoriam in acc?-->
						Ca[e]sar introduxit genus expedita[e]
						Eloquentia[e], et Industria[e], quod
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						adhuc omnes supereminet. Quodmodo ille canit; Micat inter omnes Julium Sydus. <!--JG: Can't find much about this Sydnus. Any ideas?-->
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Of what kind are the exquiste formulas of saying and doing, except as it is said and done more excellent than others? He, who not surpasses all present things, whichever by his praise, <!--JG: Not sure about 'sua quemq[ue] laude'-->
			should be ashamed. And to desire that intimately. Victory is manly. Caesar introduced the kind of expedite eloquence and industry, which hitherto rises above all. In what way does that man sing; Julius Sydnus
			trembles among all.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
